---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { siteFromHost } from '../../content';

const site = siteFromHost();
const path = '/compare/drip-vs-postscript';
const title = 'Drip vs Postscript for Shopify: 2026 Comparison';
const desc = 'Drip vs Postscript for Shopify stores — visual email workflow control vs SMS-native specialization, stack architecture, compliance, and team fit.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is Drip or Postscript better for a Shopify store doing $80k/mo?',
    answer: 'Neither alone. Drip owns email lifecycle with visual workflow control — welcome, cart, post-purchase, winback. Postscript owns SMS with superior compliance, two-way conversations, and keyword campaigns. At $80k/mo, most stores need Drip (or similar ESP) for email plus Postscript for SMS depth. Postscript cannot replace Drip\'s email canvas; Drip cannot match Postscript\'s SMS specialization.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can Postscript replace Drip entirely?',
    answer: 'No for most stores. Postscript is SMS-first — it does not replace Drip\'s email depth, visual workflow canvas, or behavior-based branching. Typical architecture: Drip for email automation, Postscript for SMS broadcasts and conversational recovery. Some stores use Drip for moderate SMS when volume is low, but SMS-heavy brands outgrow Drip text quickly.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How does Drip vs Postscript pricing compare?',
    answer: 'Drip bills on people in account — typically $120–200/mo at 12k contacts. Postscript uses plan plus usage-based messaging — transparent for SMS-heavy stores but spikes during flash sales. Model promotional SMS volume explicitly for BFCM. Combined stack cost often exceeds either platform alone — justify with attributable SMS revenue.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I use Drip and Postscript together?',
    answer: 'Common when SMS drives 15%+ of retention revenue. Drip owns email workflows with canvas visibility; Postscript owns SMS drop alerts, cart recovery texts, and keyword opt-in. Sync suppression to prevent duplicate cart touches across channels. The mistake is paying for both without coordination logic or shared exclusion rules.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I also consider Sequenzy instead of Drip or Postscript?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy handles email lifecycle with pay-per-email pricing — pair with Postscript for SMS depth. Drip still wins for visual workflow purists who want canvas control. Sequenzy plus Postscript is a lean stack for guided email strategy and specialized SMS without Drip maintenance overhead.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which has better TCPA compliance tooling?',
    answer: 'Postscript leads for SMS-specific compliance — keywords, opt-out handling, quiet hours, and conversational consent flows. Drip SMS compliance is solid but email-native teams may underestimate TCPA risk at scale. High SMS revenue stores should weigh Postscript guardrails seriously before relying on Drip text alone.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which handles cart abandonment better?',
    answer: 'Depends on channel. Drip email cart workflows excel at branching by discount sensitivity, purchase history, and tag logic — strong for education-first recovery on higher AOV. Postscript SMS cart recovery wins on immediacy for mobile-first flash drops — streetwear, limited releases, drop-day urgency. Best results combine Drip email with Postscript SMS, not either alone.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What workflow test should decide the winner?',
    answer: 'For email: build welcome (branch by signup source), three-step cart (winback suppression), post-purchase cross-sell — Drip wins. For SMS: cart abandonment text, flash broadcast with quiet hours, keyword opt-in, two-way reply — Postscript wins SMS tests. Most stores need Drip (or similar ESP) plus optional Postscript — not Postscript alone as a full retention stack.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="py-14 md:py-20">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="mb-8 text-sm">
        <a class="link" href="/compare">Comparisons</a>
        <span class="mx-2 text-[#5d3a1d]">/</span>
        <span class="text-[#5d3a1d]">Drip vs Postscript</span>
      </nav>

      <header class="max-w-4xl">
        <p class="editorial-kicker">Head-to-head</p>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-5">Drip vs Postscript for Shopify</h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">
          A category mismatch merchants still search. Drip is visual email automation for operators who design behavior-based workflows on a canvas. Postscript is SMS infrastructure that assumes email lives elsewhere. We evaluated both through a $92k/mo streetwear label pairing Drip email nurture with Postscript drop alerts, a supplements shop that wrongly treated Postscript as its only marketing platform, and a $58k/mo skincare brand whose retention owner built custom cart branching in Drip while outsourcing SMS to Postscript.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="mt-12 max-w-4xl">
        <TldrBox
          picks={[
            { label: 'Email workflows', tool: 'Drip', reason: 'Visual canvas for branching, tags, and behavior triggers.' },
            { label: 'SMS specialization', tool: 'Postscript', reason: 'Compliance, two-way text, and Shopify SMS focus.' },
            { label: 'Operator control', tool: 'Drip', reason: 'Hands-on logic without enterprise overhead.' },
            { label: 'SMS revenue focus', tool: 'Postscript', reason: 'When text is a primary channel, not an add-on.' },
            { label: 'Also consider', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Email playbooks paired with Postscript for SMS depth.' },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12 card overflow-x-auto">
        <h2 class="px-5 py-4 font-serif text-2xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Comparison at a glance</h2>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Drip</th><th>Postscript</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Best for</td><td>Visual email workflow operators</td><td>SMS-native Shopify marketing</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Starting price</td><td>From ~$39/mo</td><td>Usage-based plans</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Email</td><td>Core product</td><td>Not primary</td></tr>
            <tr><td>SMS depth</td><td>Moderate — journey-integrated</td><td>Best-in-class for Shopify</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Workflow UI</td><td>Visual canvas</td><td>SMS automations</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Compliance</td><td>Solid for email</td><td>SMS-first guardrails</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Shopify depth</td><td>Native — orders, tags, products</td><td>Native — SMS events</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Typical role</td><td>Primary email ESP</td><td>SMS layer in combined stack</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl">
        <h2>Why this comparison matters for Shopify merchants</h2>
        <p>
          Drip and Postscript solve different problems — yet merchants search them head-to-head because both appear in Shopify app stores and both touch retention revenue. Drip assumes your team wants to design email journeys from a visual canvas with every branch auditable. Postscript assumes SMS is serious enough to warrant dedicated infrastructure, compliance tooling, and conversational recovery. The streetwear label needed both: Drip for post-purchase education and browse nurture, Postscript for Thursday drop texts that convert in minutes.
        </p>
        <p>
          The supplements shop made the expensive mistake of evaluating Postscript as a Klaviyo replacement. They launched SMS cart recovery and keyword campaigns — strong results on text — but had no equivalent for welcome series, post-purchase cross-sell, or winback. Eight weeks later they added Drip for email and spent another month syncing suppression between platforms. Postscript was never wrong; treating it as a full ESP was.
        </p>

        <h2>Workflow test: welcome and onboarding</h2>
        <p>
          Drip built welcome on canvas with explicit nodes for popup vs footer signup, first-product-viewed branch, and SMS opt-in handoff to Postscript via tag sync. Build time: one afternoon for an experienced operator. Postscript offers SMS welcome sequences and keyword opt-in flows — excellent for text-first acquisition — but no email welcome depth. For brands where email still drives 60–80% of automation revenue, Drip owns this test.
        </p>
        <p>
          The skincare brand wanted welcome email three to feature the category of first product viewed, then SMS opt-in on email two for restock alerts. Drip handled email branching; Postscript received tagged subscribers for SMS-only journeys. Clean handoff — but required documented tag rules both teams understood before BFCM edits.
        </p>

        <h2>Workflow test: abandoned cart</h2>
        <p>
          Drip's cart workflow showed exactly which branch fired for discount-sensitive tags — valuable when the streetwear label A/B tested education vs 10% off in step two. Cross-journey suppression — exclude shoppers in active winback — was tighter in Drip's visual rules after setup. Postscript cart texts fired faster on mobile — incremental recovery on drop-day urgency when email sat unopened for four hours.
        </p>
        <p>
          Best practice for the streetwear label: Drip email steps one and three, Postscript text at step two for mobile shoppers who opted into SMS. Coordinated timing required shared exclusion lists — shoppers who purchased via email step one never received the Postscript text. Without that sync, duplicate touches eroded margin and annoyed VIPs.
        </p>

        <h2>Pricing reality for combined stacks</h2>
        <p>
          At 15k contacts, Drip typically lands $150–240/mo. Postscript adds plan plus per-message costs — moderate promotional volume can run $200–400/mo depending on broadcast frequency. Combined TCO exceeds either alone. Justify with attributable SMS revenue: if Postscript drives 20% of recovered carts at $95 AOV, the stack math works. If SMS is occasional, Drip-only or Drip plus lighter SMS may suffice.
        </p>
        <p>
          Flash sale weeks spike Postscript bills unpredictably. Budget BFCM SMS volume explicitly — the streetwear label modeled three broadcast tiers and set Postscript spend caps. Drip billing stays contact-based; list hygiene on popup imports matters before January renewal.
        </p>

        <h2>Shopify data depth in production</h2>
        <p>
          Drip goes deep on custom fields, tag-driven logic, and product-based delays when Shopify customer metadata is rich. Postscript focuses on SMS-relevant events — cart, order, browse, keyword — with compliance-first data handling. Neither replaces the other on data depth; they complement when email logic and SMS urgency serve different moments in the journey.
        </p>
        <p>
          The skincare brand's irregular replenishment cadence — 28 to 60 days by product line — lived naturally in Drip's canvas with custom delays. Postscript handled restock SMS for subscribers who explicitly opted into text alerts. Email owned education; SMS owned urgency. Splitting channels by intent beat forcing one platform to do both poorly.
        </p>

        <h2>Team fit: who should choose which</h2>
        <p><strong>Choose Drip if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Your retention owner thinks in workflows and wants canvas visibility for email</li>
          <li>Custom branching by tags, custom fields, and purchase behavior is central</li>
          <li>You will A/B test email journey paths frequently</li>
          <li>SMS is secondary — or you will pair a dedicated SMS tool like Postscript</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Choose Postscript if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>SMS drives 15%+ of attributable retention revenue with dedicated ownership</li>
          <li>Two-way conversations, keyword campaigns, and TCPA guardrails matter</li>
          <li>Drop-day urgency and mobile-first flash catalogs define your channel mix</li>
          <li>Email already lives in Drip, Klaviyo, or another ESP — Postscript is the SMS layer</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Also consider Sequenzy</h2>
        <p>
          If Drip's canvas feels like maintenance debt and you still need email depth alongside Postscript SMS, Sequenzy offers guided lifecycle playbooks with pay-per-email pricing and unlimited contacts. It will not replace Postscript's SMS specialization or Drip's visual workflow purism. It can replace the strategic blank page — what flows to run, in what order, with what suppression — while Postscript handles text urgency.
        </p>

        <h2>Tag sync specification for Drip-to-Postscript handoff</h2>
        <p>
          Minimum shared tags: SMS opt-in confirmed, cart-active flag, wholesale exclusion, discount-sensitive, purchased-suppress-until. Streetwear label synced tags hourly during sale week — Postscript broadcast segment excluded cart-active and wholesale-tagged profiles Drip email already touched. Shared order ID suppression prevented VIP double-touch incident in month four from recurring.
        </p>
        <p>
          Skincare irregular replenishment lived in Drip canvas; Postscript restock SMS only for subscribers who explicitly opted into text alerts on email two — email owned education, SMS owned urgency. Splitting by intent beat forcing one platform to handle both poorly.
        </p>

        <h2>BFCM spend cap planning for Postscript</h2>
        <p>
          Model three broadcast tiers before flash season — 25%, 50%, 100% of opted-in list — with message fee ceiling finance approves. Streetwear label set $4k Postscript cap for Memorial Day; Drip billing stayed contact-based regardless of send frequency. Flash weeks spike SMS bills unpredictably; caps prevent finance surprise without blocking revenue if ROI threshold met mid-campaign.
        </p>

        <h2>Merchant scenario: streetwear label coordinated cart stack</h2>
        <p>
          At $78k/mo this label ran Drip for post-purchase education and browse nurture while Postscript owned Thursday drop texts converting in minutes. Cart abandonment used Drip email steps one and three with Postscript text at step two for mobile shoppers who opted into SMS — shared exclusion on order ID prevented duplicate touches after email step one converted.
        </p>
        <p>
          Memorial Day sale week: retention owner edited Drip canvas excluding clearance inventory from full-price upsells; Postscript broadcast segment excluded active cart abandoners. Coordinated timing required weekly tag sync review — failure mode documented in runbook after one VIP received cart text and winback email same hour in month four.
        </p>

        <h2>90-day rollout: email canvas plus SMS layer activation</h2>
        <p>
          Weeks 1–4: Build welcome and cart in Drip with SMS opt-in handoff tags to Postscript — document tag rules both platforms understand. Do not evaluate Postscript as Klaviyo replacement; email four-flow test lives in Drip first.
        </p>
        <p>
          Weeks 5–8: Activate Postscript cart SMS at step two for mobile opt-ins only. Measure incremental recovery versus Drip email-only control on same AOV band. Add keyword opt-in if TikTok or packaging insert growth is strategic.
        </p>
        <p>
          Weeks 9–12: Model combined TCO at BFCM broadcast volume — set Postscript spend caps. List hygiene on Drip popup imports before January renewal; flash weeks spike SMS bills unpredictably.
        </p>

        <h2>Margin math: Drip plus Postscript combined stack</h2>
        <p>
          At 15k contacts: Drip $190/mo plus Postscript $280/mo average equals $470/mo combined. Streetwear label attributed 22% of recovered carts to Postscript SMS at $95 AOV — $4,800/mo incremental justified stack premium over Drip-only.
        </p>
        <p>
          Supplements shop mistake: Postscript-only eight weeks, then added Drip — migration month cost $2k operator labor. Starting Drip-first with Postscript when SMS exceeds 15% attributable revenue avoids rebuild tax.
        </p>

        <h2>Email-primary versus SMS-primary stack ordering</h2>
        <p>
          Build Drip email four-flow foundation first — welcome, cart, post-purchase, winback — before Postscript SMS layer activation. Supplements shop reversed order and paid eight-week gap plus migration labor. Streetwear label built Drip first, added Postscript when drop SMS exceeded 15% attributable revenue — correct sequencing avoided rebuild tax.
        </p>
        <p>
          Combined stack TCO $470/mo at 15k contacts justified when SMS attributable revenue exceeds $4k/mo incremental — simple ROI gate finance understands. Below gate, Drip-only with embedded SMS opt-in collection for future Postscript add is sufficient interim.
        </p>

        <h2>Failure rehearsal: platform category errors</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Postscript replacing email ESP.</strong> Strong SMS, no welcome or winback for eight weeks — supplements shop paid migration cost to add Drip. SMS layer, not full stack.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Drip-only when drop-day SMS drives launch revenue.</strong> Email unopened four hours on mobile — Postscript text urgency recovers incremental carts Drip email cannot match on flash cadence.
        </p>

        <h2>Weekly operator checklist during coordinated stack trial</h2>
        <p>
          Monday: tag sync audit between Drip and Postscript — SMS opt-in, cart-active, purchased-suppress. Wednesday: attributed recovery split email versus SMS on abandoned carts. Friday: Postscript message fee week-to-date versus cap. Sale week: Drip canvas clearance exclusion plus Postscript broadcast segment excluding cart-active profiles — streetwear label Memorial Day drill completed in 22 minutes combined.
        </p>
        <p>
          Month one post-Postscript add: incremental SMS-attributed cart recovery must exceed Postscript incremental fee or stack reconsider — streetwear cleared $4,800/mo bar at $280/mo average Postscript cost. Supplements shop negative ROI month one triggered Drip email rebuild that should have preceded Postscript — sequencing lesson applied retroactively.
        </p>

        <p>
          Postscript add timing: when SMS attributable revenue crosses 15% of retention total OR drop-day broadcasts exceed two per quarter, dedicated SMS layer justified. Below threshold, collect SMS opt-ins in Drip welcome email two and defer Postscript until list and send volume support specialization. Streetwear cleared threshold month three; supplements shop should have built Drip email first — reversed order cost migration month.
        </p>

        <h2>Final pre-decision audit</h2>
        <p>
          Stack sequencing verification: Drip four-flow email live and attributed before Postscript add unless SMS already exceeds 15% retention revenue at trial start — supplements shop reversal cost one migration month. Tag sync test order weekly during trial: purchase after email step one must suppress Postscript text within five minutes — streetwear VIP incident prevention requires automated not manual suppression.
        </p>
        <p>
          BFCM Postscript cap pre-approved in finance system before October — streetwear $4k Memorial Day cap prevented mid-campaign finance panic while allowing ROI-positive send continuation when attributed revenue cleared threshold hour three of six-hour drop window. Drip-plus-Postscript stacks fail without shared suppression infrastructure — budget tag sync maintenance as line item, not afterthought. Build Drip email four-flow foundation before Postscript SMS layer every time.
        </p>

        <p><em>Minimum viable trial length: 90 days with weekly operator checklist — shorter trials miss sale-week edit safety and billing cycle surprises both platforms surface only under operational stress. Document baseline metrics in week one before any platform change claim.</em></p>

        <h2>Channel architecture: Drip email plus Postscript SMS stack</h2>
        <p>
          Accessories brand $52k/mo outgrew Drip SMS limits — Postscript added for drop-night texts while Drip retained email canvas. Suppression map: Drip cart email three blocks Postscript SMS within six hours. Postscript-only evaluation failed because email workflow depth was not there; Drip-only SMS underperformed on TCPA tooling. Combined stack $380/mo versus failed single-vendor path.
        </p>

        <h2>Verdict</h2>
        <p>
          Drip wins email workflow control; Postscript wins SMS specialization. Most Shopify stores at scale need both in a coordinated stack — not a winner-take-all choice. Run the four-flow email test on Drip and the SMS compliance test on Postscript. If you are choosing only one platform, pick Drip for email-primary retention and add Postscript when SMS revenue justifies dedicated infrastructure. The supplements shop learned that lesson at migration cost.
        </p>
      </article>

      <div class="mt-10 max-w-4xl text-sm">
        <p class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Related comparisons</p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          <a class="link" href="/compare/klaviyo-vs-postscript">Klaviyo vs Postscript</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/omnisend-vs-postscript">Omnisend vs Postscript</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/sequenzy-vs-drip">Sequenzy vs Drip</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/for/fashion">Email apps for fashion</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/use-cases/abandoned-cart">Abandoned cart playbook</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Drip vs Postscript FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
